	keywords = {campaign-messageTiming, elections, interaction-pullOnly, massMedia, opinions-discrete, opinions-scalar, parties-two, receptivity-impressionFormation, receptivity-RAS, seminal, topology-graph, turnout, turnout-attitudeStrength},
	annote = {Diff from us:
Nothing in here about opinion space, voters finding objectively-best candidates based on issue opinions, or campaigns using position shifts to seek new voters. Citizens use “mental accounting” (essentially, maintaining a scoreboard for how much they like party A vs B over time).
Influence includes a mass media component and a party leaders component (in addition to the fellow-voter influence), but always in a good-or-bad way, not an issue-based way. (All the messages try to convince voters that party X is good or party Y is bad.)
The ways in which voters influence each other is complex, and worth looking at. Not every interaction between voters is efficacious. Their dynamic is based on the RAS model (Zaller 1992), impression formation (Lodge 1995), and attitude strength.
The “campaign strategies” are much different than ours -- rather than chasing votes by adopting issue positions, their campaigns decide when to deploy resources during the campaign to try and maximize their effectiveness. (Want to influence a voter early enough for them to lock-in, but late enough that they remember and are motivated to vote, etc.)
Voters have different “degrees of interest” in the election, which affects not only their likelihood to vote, but what their inter-citizen influence dynamics are like.
Only two parties, A and B.
},
